  "prompt": "What is 6/6 myopia vision?",
  "response": "6/6 vision is a term used to describe normal visual acuity measured at a distance of 6 meters. It means that a person with 6/6 vision can see what should normally be seen at that distance.\n\nMyopia, on the other hand, is a condition where a person has difficulty seeing distant objects clearly because their eyes can focus objects better when they are closer. This is often due to the eye being longer than normal or the cornea being too curved.\n\nTherefore, \"6/6 myopia vision\" can be confusing because 6/6 implies normal vision, while myopia indicates a difficulty with distance vision. It might be more accurate to simply refer to \"myopia\" indicating nearsightedness, where visual acuity is less than 6/6 at 6 meters without corrective lenses.\n\nIf someone with myopia achieves 6/6 vision, it typically means they are wearing corrective lenses (glasses or contact lenses) that compensate for their nearsightedness, allowing them to see at a normal acuity level at distance.",
